The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Latin American trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous close.  The  MSCI Latin America Index  fell 0.5 percent to 4,583.72.
In Brazil, preferred shares usually are the most-traded class of
stock.  Brazil  Tecnisa SA  (TCSA3 BS): The developer reported third-quarter
contracted sales of 423.2 million reais, of which 385.2 million
reais were exclusive to the company, according to a regulatory
filing. New projects amounted to 655.5 million reais, of which
573.6 million reais were exclusive to the company. The stock
fell 2.1 percent to 10.20 reais.  Chile  Cencosud SA  (CENCOSUD CC): Chileâ€™s largest retailer by
sales agreed to pay 1.35 billion reais for Brazilian supermarket
operator Bretas. Cencosud fell 1.6 percent 3,239.9 pesos.  Colombia  Helm Bank SA  (PFBHELMB CB): The Colombian lender plans to
sell as much as 400 billion pesos ($221.2 million) of bonds in
the local market on Oct. 28. Helm Bank fell 1 percent to 494
pesos.  Mexico  Grupo Carso SAB  (GCARSOA1 MM): The holding company
controlled billionaire Carlos Slim, said its mining unit hedged
the price for part of its future output of gold, copper and
other metals for the next three years. Forty-three percent of
gold output was hedged over three years for $1,189 an ounce,
Carso said today in a statement to the Mexican stock exchange.
The Mexico City-based company also agreed to the short-term
hedging contracts for 26 percent of its silver output at $18.71
an ounce, 61 percent of its copper production at $3.32 a pound,
39 percent of zinc at $1.08 a pound, and 28 percent of lead at
$1.04 a pound. Carso climbed 1.7 percent to 73.32 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
